    longDescription: 'The original Legend of Zelda score had to work within the NES hardware\'s limitations while serving a new kind of game: an open-world action adventure with no fixed path, where players might spend extended time in any given area. Kondo responded by composing music that could sustain longer loops without fatigue — the overworld theme is structurally designed to feel like it is always arriving at something new, even as it repeats. The dungeon theme used a minor-key drone and sparse, dissonant figures to create unease appropriate for enclosed, dangerous spaces. The title screen fanfare — the short brass motif that became the Zelda series\' signature — was composed as an introduction to the overworld theme but has since been used independently across the franchise as the franchise\'s musical logo.',
